Thus, for any positive integer $n$, we always have $f(3 n)=3 f(n)$.
We now prove that $f(n)=n f(1)$ (i.e., satisfying (1) does not satisfy (2)).
If not, there exists a positive integer $m$ such that $f(m) \neq m f(1)$. We choose $m$ to be the smallest positive integer satisfying $f(m) \neq m f(1)$, then $m \geq 5$ and is odd (otherwise, if $m$ is even, by the minimality of $m$, we have $f\left(\frac{m}{2}\right)=\frac{m}{2} f(1)$, thus $f(m)=2 f\left(\frac{m}{2}\right)=m f(1)$, a contradiction). Since $m \geq 5$, we have $\frac{m-3}{2}<\frac{m+3}{2}<m$, and by the minimality of $m$, we have $f\left(\frac{m-3}{2}\right)=\frac{m-3}{2} \cdot f(1), f\left(\frac{m+3}{2}\right)=\frac{m+3}{2} \cdot f(1)$. If $\frac{m+3}{2}$ and $\frac{m-3}{2}$ are the same color, then $f(m)=f\left(\frac{m+3}{2}\right)+f\left(\frac{m-3}{2}\right)=m f(1)$, a contradiction, so $\frac{m+3}{2}$ and $\frac{m-3}{2}$ are different colors, thus $m$ is exactly the same color as one of $\frac{m+3}{2}, \frac{m-3}{2}$. We consider these two cases:
